<paragraph blockId="7.[813,1420,310,698]" pageId="7" pageNumber="322">
This species can be distinguished from congeners that occur in this region by a combination of features: smooth pectoral-fin spine, 68–78 dorsal-fin rays, 58–64 anal-fin rays, moderately broad supraoccipital process, and a distinct color pattern of white spots on the sides of the body. This species is common in forested, more pristine habitats than the sympatric 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Linnaeus" baseAuthorityYear="1758" box="[1116,1257,606,630]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Clariidae" genus="Clarias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Siluriformes" pageId="7" pageNumber="322" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="batrachus">
<emphasis box="[1116,1257,606,630]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="322">C. batrachus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which is usu- ally common in more open, disturbed habitats (
<bibRefCitation author="Ambak MA &amp; Isa MM &amp; Zakaria MZ &amp; Ghaffar MA" pageId="7" pageNumber="322" refId="ref6880" refString="Ambak MA, Isa MM, Zakaria MZ, Ghaffar MA (2010) Fishes of Malaysia. Penerbit UMT, Universiti Malaysia Terengganu, Tereng- ganu, 334 pp." type="book" year="2010">Ambak et al. 2010</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
